1 Introduction

SQL stands for Structured Query Language, and is designed for interacting with data stored in relational databases - a digital database based on the relational model of data.

We use databases to efficiently store large amounts of data. Using a database allows us to find, add, edit and delete data in an easy and quick manner. Databases can be stored securely in a database, and they can in addition be accessible online, allowing multiple users to interact with them.

There are a number of times when we may want to use databases:

  • When our data is too large to store in a single csv or excel file.
  • When a number of users need access to data that is being updated.
  • When access to data needs to be restricted, such as with sensitive data.

SQL is a way of interacting with a specific type of database using something called the relational model.

A relational database is a collection of tables, each table containing a set of rows and columns. Each row contains the information for a single observation - e.g.Â a customer, a transaction, a VAT record - while each column contains a specific attribute for all rows in the data - e.g.Â a name, an id number, a transaction date.

In the below table, we have six attributes for our three observations.

pID forename age nationality hair_Colour eye_Colour
1 Alice 24 British Brown Blue
2 Bob 32 Canadian Brown Blue
3 Cleo 29 Danish Brown Blue

Here we have a unique value in the column pID, which is different for each record. This allows us to identify each record by the pID attribute rather than the other contents of the record, which may not be unique.

There are many different flavours of SQL, each with slight syntactical differences. Commands you enter to access a PostgreSQL database might have small differences to those used to access a MySQL, Oracle SQL or an SQLite table. As such, some commands might need a slight adjustment to be able to access a specific database system, but there is a wealth of documentation available online for different variants.

We can also use SQL syntax in both R and Python to interact with databases by using packages such as DBI, sqldf, dbplyr (R) and sqlite3, mysql.connector, sqlalchemy (python). In fact, this course was created in part using one of these libraries and SQLâs interactivity with R.

Please go to sqliteonline.com for all exercises. You do not need to make an account.

2 Basic SQL

For the benefit of this document, lets create some temporary data.

How this done, and the syntax below will be explained throughout the course.

You do not yet need to write these commands on your own device. If you do, you will need to run one command at a time, rather than all at once like in an R or python script. If you re-run lines of code multiple times an error may be produced.

We suggest if you do want to run the code as we go, to write the code, run it, then remove the code before writing the next statement.

-- Create an empty table with defined attributes (this line is a comment).
CREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS people (
    pid INTEGER PRIMARY KEY, 
    forename VARCHAR(255), 
    age INTEGER, 
    nationality VARCHAR(255), 
    hair_colour VARCHAR(255), 
    eye_colour VARCHAR(255)
    );
-- Insert values into the created table. 
INSERT INTO people (pid, forename, age, nationality, hair_colour, eye_colour) 
VALUES (1, 'Alice', 29, 'British', 'Brown', 'Blue'), 
       (2, 'Bob', 32, 'Canadian', 'Brown', 'Blue'), 
       (3, 'Cleo', 29, 'Danish', 'Brown', 'Blue');

In general, SQL is both case-insensitive, and ignores unnecessary whitespace.

Convention varies, but having all SQL keywords in ALL CAPITALS, and all table names and column names in all lowercase is advisable; it makes it easier to distinguish between variables and keywords.

Equally, use whitespace to your advantage to make SQL statements more readable, and do not put spaces in database, table, or column names.

All valid SQL commands end in a semi-colon - this terminates the SQL query.

-- Example casing convention. 
SQLKEYWORDS tablenames columnnames;

2.1 Types of Operation

SQL can be broadly broken into three sub-sections:

  • Querying the data,
  • Editing tables of data,
  • Editing the actual database structure.

Querying allows a user to gain insights from the data, by selecting specific data and performing operations upon it.

Inserting records, deleting records, or modifying existing records falls under the second category, editing the contents of the tables.

Editing the database structure itself includes defining tables, creating, dropping, and altering them.

2.2 Select

For much of our time interacting with a database we will be wanting to extract some information from it.

DQL (Data Query Language) is made up primarily of the SELECT keyword. This is used anytime data needs to be returned.

To select data from your table, use the SELECT statement.

This can be used to select a subset of columns FROM a table by listing them.

The column names follow the SELECT statement, and multiple columns can be selected by separating the names by commas.

In the below example we want the forename and age columns returned from the people table we created in the above section.

SELECT forename, age FROM people;
forename age
Alice 29
Bob 32
Cleo 29

All of the columns in a database can be returned by passing in a * symbol in place of the column.

SELECT * FROM people;
pid forename age nationality hair_colour eye_colour
1 Alice 29 British Brown Blue
2 Bob 32 Canadian Brown Blue
3 Cleo 29 Danish Brown Blue

We can select the DISTINCT results from a column by adding the DISTINCT keyword. This will return only the records that are unique.

The DISTINCT keyword follows the select statement.

SELECT DISTINCT hair_colour FROM people;
hair_colour
Brown

REMINDER: All valid queries must end with a ;

In SQL you can refer to a specific column name in a table using the syntax:

-- A dot after the tablename specifies which column is chosen.
tablename.columnname

An example of using dot notation for a column name would be:

SELECT people.forename FROM people;
forename
Alice
Bob
Cleo

2.2.1 Conditions

We often want more specific information than just entire columns of our data.

WHERE can be used to add conditions to SELECT statements, using logical operators. The records returned to us will only be those that meet the conditions requirements.

  • To match values, use the operator =. For example CustomerID = 10

  • To return the opposite, where values do not match, use <>. For example. CustomerID <> 10

  • > and < can be used when filtering on numeric or date columns. If used on a column of strings, they will compare on an alphabetical basis. For example a < c < d

SELECT * FROM people WHERE nationality = 'British';
pid forename age nationality hair_colour eye_colour
1 Alice 29 British Brown Blue

As our operations get longer we can separate different statements into different lines for clarity. The below code block is equivalent the the one shown above, but will be more readable.

By not ending a line with a ; we can go to the next line to write another part of the statement.

SELECT * 
FROM people 
WHERE nationality = 'British';
pid forename age nationality hair_colour eye_colour
1 Alice 29 British Brown Blue

We can combine conditions together using AND and OR, and conditions can be wrapped in brackets to perform more complicated logical comparisons.

SELECT * 
FROM people 
WHERE (nationality <> 'British') AND (age > 30);
pid forename age nationality hair_colour eye_colour
2 Bob 32 Canadian Brown Blue

Sentences are only complete when they have a proper punctuation mark at the end (. ! ? etc.). In a similar manner SQL statements are only complete once a ; has been added to the end.


2.2.1.1 In

IN can be used to return records where a value is IN a list of values.

A list of values is formed using () and commas.

pid 5 and 9 will not show, as they do not exist in this table.

SELECT *
FROM people
WHERE pid IN (1, 5, 9);
pid forename age nationality hair_colour eye_colour
1 Alice 29 British Brown Blue


2.2.1.2 NOT

We can invert conditions by including the NOT keyword before a condition. This will return us the values that were not returned in the last example.

SELECT *
FROM people
WHERE pid NOT IN (1, 5, 9);
pid forename age nationality hair_colour eye_colour
2 Bob 32 Canadian Brown Blue
3 Cleo 29 Danish Brown Blue


2.2.1.3 LIKE

LIKE can be used as part of the condition to apply fuzzy matching techniques. Fuzzy matching in general returns non-exactly specified queries.

There are two wildcard operators which can be used, to look for a single character, or multiple characters, *_, and %*.

For instance, LIKE âp_nâ would match to pan, pin, or pen, but not to person, or penguin, as it only matches single character replacements.

LIKE âp%nâ however, will look for any number of characters between the p and n, so both pan and penguin will be matched. This also includes matching zero characters.

SELECT * FROM people 
WHERE forename LIKE 'Alic%';
pid forename age nationality hair_colour eye_colour
1 Alice 29 British Brown Blue 
SELECT * FROM people
WHERE forename LIKE '_o%';
pid forename age nationality hair_colour eye_colour
2 Bob 32 Canadian Brown Blue

LIKE is generally case sensitive. To get around this, use the LOWER (or UPPER) keyword and wrap it around the column the filter is being applied to with brackets ().

SELECT * FROM people
WHERE LOWER(nationality) LIKE '%d%';
pid forename age nationality hair_colour eye_colour
2 Bob 32 Canadian Brown Blue
3 Cleo 29 Danish Brown Blue

In SQLite, LIKE by default will be case insensitive. It can be switched on for the session by running:

PRAGMA case_sensitive_like = true;


2.2.2 Sorting Records

Without explicitly specifying an order to return data in, there is no guarantee that the data will be in any one particular order when returned - it will not default to being sorted on an index number (the primary key).

The ORDER BY keyword can be used to specify a specific column, or columns, to order in ascending, or descending order.

For descending order we use DESC after the ORDER BY columnname.

We can similarly use ASC for ascending order.

SELECT * 
FROM people
ORDER BY forename DESC;
pid forename age nationality hair_colour eye_colour
3 Cleo 29 Danish Brown Blue
2 Bob 32 Canadian Brown Blue
1 Alice 29 British Brown Blue

We can sort by multiple columns by chaining column names and order methods like below.

SELECT * 
FROM people
ORDER BY age ASC, nationality DESC;
pid forename age nationality hair_colour eye_colour
3 Cleo 29 Danish Brown Blue
1 Alice 29 British Brown Blue
2 Bob 32 Canadian Brown Blue

REMINDER: The order you list the columns in will affect how the data is sorted. The first column will be sorted by first, then within each unique value the next column will be sorted according to the method listed.

2.3 Arithmetic

We can do more than just simply return specified values, as we are using a programming language we can do arithmetic between our columns to return more informative values.

The arithmetic operators include:

  • + (Add)
  • - (Subtract)
  • *** (Multiply)
  • / (Divide)
  • % (Modulo)

We can therefore get values by performing operations on columns. This can be done either as combinations of columns or to individual columns. For example:

SELECT forename, age * 365 
FROM people;
forename age * 365
Alice 10585
Bob 11680
Cleo 10585

The basic syntax for operations is:

SELECT [column1] [operation] [column2]
FROM [tablename];

Whilst not being a hugely informative measurement, we can multiply the columns pID and age using the following code.

SELECT pID * age
FROM people;
pID * age
29
64
87

This is useful for scaling or combining values, for example, quantities such as cost_per_person could be calculated using the columns cost and number_of_people.

2.4 Aggregates

We will often want to find out aggregate quantities which tell us something about our data.

Examples of aggregates we can use include:

  • COUNT() - counts the number of records
  • SUM() - returns the sum of the values of the records
  • AVG() - returns the mean average of the values of records

These can be particularly useful when used in conjunction with other conditions, allowing us to summarise specific parts of our data.

These are all functions, so they require brackets and us to pass arguments into them.

NOTE: NULL values are ignored in these statistics.

Below we will find:

  • the number of records.
  • the total age of all people with blue eyes.
  • the average age of all people with names starting with âAâ.
SELECT COUNT(pid) FROM people;
COUNT(pid)
3 
SELECT SUM(age) 
FROM people
WHERE eye_colour = 'Blue';
SUM(age)
90 
SELECT AVG(age) 
FROM people
WHERE forename LIKE 'A%';
AVG(age)
29

2.5 Comments and Whitespace

All single line comments should start with two dashes: â. Anything after these will be ignored.

--DROP TABLE people

For multiple line comments we use/ to open the comment and / to close them. This is especially useful for commenting out blocks of code.

/*
DROP TABLE people
DROP TABLE personaldata
*/

Likewise, excess whitespace is ignored. Commands can run on multiple lines, with as much whitespace as needed to make the entire command easy to understand (or, in the case below, make the code less legible!).

SELECT     * 

     FROM

  people
              WHERE 

eye_colour IS        'Blue';
pid forename age nationality hair_colour eye_colour
1 Alice 29 British Brown Blue
2 Bob 32 Canadian Brown Blue
3 Cleo 29 Danish Brown Blue

Be sensible with your whitespace! If you would like further guidance on specific syntax there are multiple style guides available online, such as this one.

Your best bet will be using your team/departmentâs style guide if it exists.

SIDE NOTE: You may see in other peoples code comments using /* and */ to begin and end comments. This is another valid form of commenting.

3 Data Tables

There are a wide range of properties of data tables themselves we will need to take into account if we want to be able to query, create and manipulate them effectively.

3.1 Data Types

SQL has strict data types that are enforced on each column. They are detailed below.

SQL Data Type Traditional Data Type Notes
VARCHAR(n) String/Character Variable length (up to n)
CHAR(n) String/Character Fixed length (n)
INTEGER Integer
SERIAL Incrementing Integer Auto-Incrementing integer for Primary Key
DATE Stores in the form YYYY-MM-DD
DATETIME Form YYYY-MM-DD HH:MI:SS

When creating a new table, each column in the table needs an associated data type.

3.2 NULLs

Nulls get placed anywhere there is an absence of data. They cannot be detected using ordinary conditions, and have to use separate statements to pull them out - IS NULL and IS NOT NULL.

Depending on the flavour of your SQL, NULLs may also be shown as NAs.

INSERT INTO people (forename)
VALUES ('David');

Note: we will discuss what the code above does shortly.

SELECT * FROM people
WHERE nationality IS NULL;
pid forename age nationality hair_colour eye_colour
4 David NA NA NA NA 
SELECT * FROM people
WHERE nationality IS NOT NULL;
pid forename age nationality hair_colour eye_colour
1 Alice 29 British Brown Blue
2 Bob 32 Canadian Brown Blue
3 Cleo 29 Danish Brown Blue

pid is given an automatically incremented value of 4, because it is something called the âPrimary Keyâ, which we will now discuss.

3.3 Primary Keys

A primary key is a field in a table which uniquely identifies each record, and so each value must be unique.

Each table can only have one primary key.

If a primary key constraint has been created, then no duplicates in the primary key column(s) are allowed - uniqueness is enforced.

SELECT * FROM people;
pid forename age nationality hair_colour eye_colour
1 Alice 29 British Brown Blue
2 Bob 32 Canadian Brown Blue
3 Cleo 29 Danish Brown Blue
4 David NA NA NA NA

The people table has the pid column as its primary key, so an error is thrown if a duplicate value tries to be inserted.

-- There already exists a key with the value = 1.
INSERT INTO people VALUES (1, 'Alicia', 24, 'British', 'Brown', 'Blue');

Error: UNIQUE constraint failed: people.pid Execution halted

Its recommended to use an automatically incrementing integer as each tableâs primary key, rather than a value tied to each individual such as an email address. Itâs important to consider whether you can guarentee a unique column will be unique no matter how the data changes, what happens if the same individual submits a request twice?

An email address, while nominally unique, is likely to be changed, or reassigned which can cause issues with any links to other data tables.

SIDE NOTE: the primary key can consist of multiple columns - a composite key.

3.4 Foreign Keys

Foreign keys are columns or combinations of columns used to link two tables together - the foreign key in a set of data refers to the primary key in another set of data.

While foreign keys do not need to be unique, if the column has been formally defined as a foreign key, it will prevent associated primary key records from being deleted.

To ensure foreign keys work with SQLite, a PRAGMA may need to be set. These are only found in SQLite, and represent global variables. One can be set to make LIKE commands case sensitive. The PRAGMA will only need to be run once per session.

PRAGMA foreign_keys = ON;
-- We create a new table `transactions`
-- You can see there are PRIMARY KEY and FOREIGN KEY keywords
CREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS transactions (
    transaction_id INTEGER PRIMARY KEY, 
    customer_id INTEGER,
    product_code INTEGER, 
    product_name VARCHAR(255), 
    quantity INTEGER,
    FOREIGN KEY(customer_id) REFERENCES people(pid)
);

Within the above SQL FOREIGN KEY line, we denote the customer_id column as referring to the pid column within the original people table.

This reference ensures that only records with a customer_id matching a people.pid can be created, and protects any records within the people table which have an pid in use within transactions.

-- Inserting records into the table.
INSERT INTO transactions (transaction_id, customer_id, product_code, product_name, quantity) 
VALUES (1, 1, 531141, 'Red Door', 4), 
       (2, 1, 532413, 'Sofa', 1), 
       (3, 3, 531941, 'Blue Lamp', 2);
-- Insert a new record with a consumer_id with no corresponding people.pid value
INSERT INTO transactions VALUES(4, 22, 533819, 'Green Lamp', 23);

Error: FOREIGN KEY constraint failed Execution halted

This error is returned, as 22 does not exist in the primary key ID column of people, and so the above record cannot be inserted into transactions.

This is useful as it enforces our two tables being connected.

-- Remove a value within a foreign key attribute.
DELETE FROM people WHERE pid = 1;

Error: FOREIGN KEY constraint failed Execution halted

The same error is returned, this time because there is a transaction with a foreign key of 1, so the people record with a pid of one is protected.

3.5 Cascade

To get around this issue, of records being protected by primary key / foreign key interactions, CASCADE can be used. CASCADE will take any changes in a table, and propogate (or cascade) them through any related tables.

If a record which is referred to elsewhere is deleted, all connected records will also be deleted - for instance, all transactions for an individual will be deleted.


We create the transactions table with CASCADE.

-- We define a FOREIGN KEY and REFERENCE
-- We then tell the data base to CASCADE
-- when we UPDATE or DELETE
CREATE TABLE transactions (
    transaction_id INTEGER PRIMARY KEY, 
    customer_id INTEGER,
    product_code INTEGER, 
    product_name VARCHAR(255), 
    quantity INTEGER,
    FOREIGN KEY(customer_id) 
      REFERENCES people(pid) 
      ON DELETE CASCADE
      ON UPDATE CASCADE
);

We populate the transactions table with records.

INSERT INTO transactions (transaction_id, customer_id, product_code, product_name, quantity) 
VALUES (1, 1, 531141, 'Red Door', 4), 
       (2, 1, 532413, 'Sofa', 1), 
       (3, 3, 531941, 'Blue Lamp', 2);
SELECT * FROM transactions;

And this time, as CASCADE has been enabled, the record can be dropped, as well as any related transactions.

DELETE FROM people WHERE pid = 1;
SELECT * FROM people;
SELECT * FROM transactions;

COUNT(*) - COUNT(name)
1

Here we are counting how many total records we have, then subtracting the number of non-missing values present. Using COUNT(name) returns us the number of non-missing values in the column.

4 Data Manipulation

INSERT, UPDATE and DELETE are three commands which are used to manipulate the data stored within an SQL table.

We have seen them used to help do other processes earlier in the course, we will now look at them in detail.


4.1 Insert

INSERT is used to insert records into existing tables of data.

Any inserted records will have to conform to any primary/foreign key constraints which have been set up:

  • No duplication of primary keys.
  • No adding non-existent foreign keys.
-- Specify the table, then columns, and then the values 
-- of the corresponding columns.
INSERT INTO table_name (column_1, column_2, ...) 
VALUES (value_1, value_2, ...);

If a new record with values for every column is being inserted, no column details need to be specified, but the order of values must match the order of columns.

This is where our data types can come into play.

For example, if a column needs CHAR type, it will not allow 27 to be inserted.

INSERT INTO people 
VALUES (4, 'Dani', 34, 'Irish', 'Black', 'Brown');
SELECT * FROM people;

We can check what data type each value in a column is by using the typeof() function.

SELECT typeof(pid) FROM people;

If we do not specify the value of a column to be inserted, it will automatically take a NULL/NA.

-- We are not giving data for all columns
INSERT INTO people (pid, forename) 
VALUES (5, 'Eric');

We can see what happens if we do not give all columns values.

SELECT * FROM people;

4.2 Update

UPDATE is used to change existing records in a table of data.

To change the values of records we use the following syntax.

UPDATE table_name
SET column_1 = value_1, column_2 = value_2 ...
WHERE condition;

Any record which matches the condition will be modified - if no WHERE statement is included, every record will be changed! To check whether the condition chosen returns only the record(s) which need to be changed, performing

SELECT * FROM table_name WHERE condition;

before modifying the table is advisable.

Below is an example of updating a value in one column.


We want to change the name âAliceâ to âAliciaâ

We first check the WHERE condition we want to use.

SELECT * 
FROM people 
WHERE forename = 'Alice';

We can see that this returns just the one record we would like to change, so we will use this condition to update the value.

UPDATE people
SET forename = 'Alicia'
WHERE forename = 'Alice';

The new forename that was updated using the WHERE condition is shown.

SELECT * FROM people;

4.3 Delete

DELETE is used to delete existing records in a table of data.

We can determine which records to delete by using a WHERE condition.

DELETE FROM table_name
WHERE condition;

As with UPDATE, care should be had when specifying a condition to filter by.

Without the WHERE clause every record will be deleted.

DELETE FROM people
WHERE forename = 'Bob';

We can see here that our data table no longer contains a record where the forename = âBobâ.

SELECT * FROM people;

5 Joining Data

5.1 Performing Joins

When linking data from separate tables, there are four main ways of linking the data. For a common column to both tables, often a Primary Key and Foreign Key pairing, the data can be joined via a:

  • Left Join
  • Right Join
  • Inner Join
  • Outer Join.


A Left Join, the top left of the four output boxes above, returns all the data from the first table, and any data from the second data which can be linked.

Data is linked if it has the same column values.

A Right Join, the bottom left box, does the opposite, and returns all the data from the second table, and any linked data from the first.

Note: A Left Join from table a to table b, is the same as a Right Join from table b to table a.

An Inner Join, keeps only rows which have common values in both tables.

While an Outer Join keeps all data, and tries to match up what it can.

Joining has noteworthy effects when a value within the joining columns has duplicates - B in the above example.

Showing our two tables:

SELECT * FROM people;
SELECT * FROM transactions;

For the table of transaction details, to add a new column to specify customer names, we can do a Left Join as the following.

We can select all rows from a specific table by adding .* after the table name. This is equivalent to writing SELECT * FROM tablename, but used when selecting from multiple tables.

SELECT transactions.*, people.forename 
FROM transactions 
LEFT JOIN people 
ON people.pid = transactions.customer_id;

This has:

  • selected all the columns from transactions,
  • selected the forename column from people
  • joined the pid column of people, to the customer_id column of transactions

The customer_id column is a Foreign Key for the transaction table, and links it to the people table.

SQL can join on multiple columns, by adding to the condition used:

SELECT tableA.*, tableB.*
FROM tableA
LEFT JOIN tableB 
ON tableA.column1 = tableB.column2 AND tableA.column3 = tableB.column4;

And like the conditions used in WHERE statements, these can be surrounded by sets of brackets to make more complicated logical comparisons.

SELECT tableA.*, tableB.*
FROM tableA
LEFT JOIN tableB 
ON (tableA.column1 = tableB.column2 AND tableA.column3 = tableB.column4) 
  OR (tableA.column5 = tableB.column6);

5.2 Duplicate Data

5.2.1 Many-to-One and One-to-Many

If there are duplicates in only one of the tables on the joining colum, such as B in the diagram above, or the customer_id 1 in the original join example, each of these will be joined with the single value in the other table of data.

Therefore there will be some duplication of some of the data.

This is however often useful, such as in the transaction-people join above where the name of the user is desired to be attached to every transaction, regardless of whether one user has more than one transaction.

One of the advantages of joining onto a primary key column is that that column will always have unique values.

5.2.2 Many-to-Many

If however, there are duplicates in both tables, each matching value on the left, will join with each matching value on the right.


In the example diagram above, the result of the join has B values four times, as 2 x 2 = 4.

5.3 Aliasing

In the join above the table names transactions and people are repeated three times - if queries get very long, and tables have very long names, this could quickly get impractical and untenable.

Instead, table names can be aliased to a new name, and referred to by the shorter name for the rest of the query. In the below query, transactions has been aliased as t, and people has been aliased as p. There are two different ways to do this, either with, or without the AS keyword.

SELECT t.*, p.forename
-- first method with AS
FROM transactions AS t
-- second method without AS
LEFT JOIN people p 
ON p.pid = t.customer_id;

If aliasing is used in this way, all references to table names must be to the aliased version. The original table name - such as transactions or people - can only be used on the FROM and LEFT JOIN lines when the aliasing is set up. If the full names are ever used instead of t or p in the above case, errors will be thrown.

6 Database Operations

CREATE, DROP, and ALTER are three SQL commands which are used to make fundamental changes to the definitions of tables.

6.1 Create

This course so far has shown the creation of tables without much explaination of how to create them.

The syntax for creating new tables is quite straightforward, and mostly consists of a list of column names and column types, with any constraints added in.

The first line, CREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS people ( will create, if it does not already exist, a new table by the name of people.

Within the brackets, and on separate lines for ease-of-understanding, are lines of the form: COLUMN_NAME DATA_TYPE [CONSTRAINT],.

Some constraints can be added on the same line as the column declaration, others must be added at the end.

REMINDER: You must close brackets and end SQL statements with ;

CREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS people (
    pid INTEGER PRIMARY KEY, 
    forename VARCHAR(255), 
    age INTEGER CHECK (age < 150), 
    nationality VARCHAR(255), 
    hair_colour VARCHAR(255), 
    eye_colour VARCHAR(255), 
    email_address VARCHAR(255) UNIQUE
);

Once a table is created, it can be populated using INSERT. As seen before, columns do not need to be specified if every column is being referenced.

Both of the SQL code blocks below will perform the same operation in this case.

INSERT INTO people (pid, forename, age, nationality, hair_colour, eye_colour, email_address) 
VALUES (1,'Alice', 29, 'British', 'Brown', 'Blue', 'alice@gmail.com'), 
       (2, 'Bob', 32, 'Canadian', 'Brown', 'Blue', 'bob@gmail.com'), 
       (3, 'Cleo', 29, 'Danish', 'Brown', 'Blue', 'cleo@gmail.com');
INSERT INTO people
VALUES (1,'Alice', 29, 'British', 'Brown', 'Blue', 'alice@gmail.com'), 
       (2, 'Bob', 32, 'Canadian', 'Brown', 'Blue', 'bob@gmail.com'), 
       (3, 'Cleo', 29, 'Danish', 'Brown', 'Blue', 'cleo@gmail.com');

Both methods produce:

SELECT * FROM people;

As well as the primary and foreign keys explored earlier, other constraints can be applied to limit the data which can be put into tables.

6.1.1 Check

CHECK is used to place a specific condition on a column, such as a number must be more than 0, or a date more than 1900-01-01.

In the above example, a CHECK constraint is used to ensure that the age data values are less than 150, as this is (at time of writing) an unfeasible age for a person.

INSERT INTO people(age) VALUES (160);

Error: CHECK constraint failed: people

As anticipated, an error is thrown in the table people, that its CHECK constraint has failed.

6.1.2 Unique

UNIQUE acts like a primary key, in that it requires every value placed into a column to be unique, such as an email address which while not used as a key, should be different for every user in the database.

INSERT INTO people(email_address) VALUES ('alice@gmail.com');

Error: UNIQUE constraint failed: people.email_address Execution halted

This gives an error because the email we are trying to insert here already exists in the email_address column.

6.1.3 Checking existing constraints

If we did not create the table ourselves we can check to see what constraints have been placed on the columns by querying the table. This returns the statements used to create the table.

SELECT sql FROM sqlite_master WHERE name = "people";

Whilst it is not as nicely formatted, this does give you the ability to see the CHECK conditions, data types and UNIQUE statements.

Each flavour of SQL will have a different method or command to do this, be sure to check the one which is relevant to you.

6.2 Drop

Dropping a table will delete the entire table, and all data stored within it - be very careful with its use.

DROP TABLE IF EXISTS transactions;

Remember - a database is a collection of related tables.

Likewise, an entire database can be dropped. Again, be very careful when dropping databases - all data stored in all tables will be lost!

DROP DATABASE 'sql.sqlite';

6.2.1 Little Bobby Tables - Sanitising your data inputs

https://xkcd.com/327/

The above is a cautionary tale on sanitising data inputs - allowing raw SQL to hit your databases can allow for SQL Injections - inserting malicious code which gets directly to your data.

Sometimes this can be used to return data that shouldnât be available to users. Other times, it can be used to delete tables - such as in the above example.

The studentâs name, of Robertâ); DROP TABLE Students;â would be passed to an insert command - INSERT INTO students VALUES (nameâ¦), but would escape the original command due to the â);, and then run the second command of DROP TABLE Students;, and hide the rest of the original legitimate command by prefacing it with a comment.

--legitimate value:
--name == Elaine
INSERT INTO students VALUES ('Elaine');

--sql injection
--name == Robert'); DROP TABLE students;--
INSERT INTO students VALUES ('Robert'); 
DROP TABLE students;
--');

We often prevent injections from being dangerous by altering the raw SQL to a clean and usable format. If your database takes a user input then input sanatisation is something your should really think about, although, this is beyond the scope of the course.

6.3 Alter

The ALTER command can be used to make changes to tables of data - for example adding a new column to an existing table or renaming a column.

ALTER TABLE people ADD height_cm INTEGER;

A new column being added will be filled with NULL values.

SELECT * FROM people;

ALTER can also be used to change constraints on tables - such as adding or removing primary and foreign keys. This is done simply in other flavours of SQL, using the below syntax.

NOTE: This will not work in SQLite, in order to get around the lack of this feature you need to create a new table without the constraint and drop the old one. How this is done will be shown shortly.

ALTER TABLE people DROP CONSTRAINT people_pkey;

As we dropped the transactions table in the previous section, this is successful - had the foreign key linking transactions to people still existed, the primary key of people would be protected.

Now that the primary key condition has been removed, a record with a duplicate id can be inserted.

INSERT INTO people 
VALUES (1, 'Alice2', 20, 'British', 'Black', 'Blue', 'alice2@gmail.com', 130);
SELECT * FROM people;

6.3.1 Renaming Columns

We have briefly mentioned that you can rename columns using the ALTER keyword. Whilst this is true for the vast majority of SQL flavours, and most likely possible for the flavour you will eventually be working with, it is not the case for sqlite. It does not have every functionality, it is lite after all.

Below are examples of how you would rename the column age to age_years using Oracle SQL and sqlite. You can see that the Oracle method is clearer and shorter.

Oracle

We can simply use the RENAME keyword to change the column name.

ALTER TABLE people
RENAME COLUMN age TO age_years;

sqlite

In order to change the name of a column in sqlite we need to create a new table with the right column names and then move the data in the original table to the new table.

-- Rename the table for clarity
ALTER TABLE people RENAME TO people_original;

-- Create the table with the new column names
CREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS people (
    pid INTEGER, 
    forename VARCHAR(255), 
    age_YEARS INTEGER, 
    nationality VARCHAR(255), 
    hair_colour VARCHAR(255), 
    eye_colour VARCHAR(255),
    email_address VARCHAR(255) UNIQUE,
    height_cm INTEGER
);

-- Insert the original data into the new table
INSERT INTO people SELECT * FROM people_original;

-- Drop the original table
DROP TABLE people_original;

This method is clearly not as simple, but thatâs okay as sqlite would rarely be used in practice, but it is very useful for learning with!

8 Futher Study

We have looked at simple, small database systems in this course. Large and more complex systems may have more strict requirements in order to operate. Below are some general topics that you should consider reading about in order to deepen your understanding of databases.

8.1 Race Conditions

Some database management systems allow queries for the same or different programs to be called at the same time (in parallel). If one query is finding the value of a record, and the other is updating the value of that same record then the order of execution will make a difference on what value is returned. This is known as a race condition.

This is a nice case study on Race Conditions.

8.2 ACID Transactions

ACID transactions are a set of properties that a database transaction can have that enforce the integrity of the database.

The acronym ACID stands for:

  • Atomicity
  • Consistency
  • Isolation
  • Durability

Good databases are created, and their transactions designed by using ACID properties.

For a primer on ACID Transactions click here.

8.3 RDBMS systems

We have so far briefly discussed that for SQL we have used relational databases. This means that values within a table can relate to other tables, this means we can run queries across multiple tables to get interesting results.

Relational Database Management Systems (RDBMS) are the programs that manage the databases themselves. These make accessing and working with the databases easier than just directly interacting with data.

Examples for RDBMS include; Oracle Database, MySQL and Microsoft SQL Server.

The RDBMS used will dictate the flavour of SQL which needs to be written in.

Why not find out which RDBMS your team / department uses?

8.4 NoSQL

Relational databases are one method of storing data, they are particularly good at storing structured data - data that is tabular and easily fits rows and columns. This, however, is not the only type of data that is stored by organisations.

Non-relational databases use unique keys to refer to specific instances of data, without using the rigid structure of related columns. This allows the database to be flexible, as the data type and size of each record can be variable. This makes non-relational database management systems particularly good at storing data such as audio, video and text files in a scalable manner.

NoSQL is a commonly used database that doesnât rely on structured data.
